    <span class="hdot"><i style="background:#56B4E9"></i> DSM-5 cue validation</span>
    <span class="hdot"><i style="background:#009E73"></i> CueFilter mitigation</span>
  </div>
  <figure class="hero-visual">
    <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-concept.jpg`} alt="Conceptual diagram showing semantic cues acting as a shortcut from speech audio to depression prediction score." />
    <figcaption class="fig-cap">Concept: semantic cues embedded in speech audio can inflate speech-only depression prediction performance if they are not explicitly audited.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <a href="#summary" class="scroll-arrow"><small>Scroll</small><i></i><span></span></a>
</section>

<!-- 2 SUMMARY -->
<section id="summary" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Summary</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">What the paper argues.</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The central claim is not that vocal biomarkers are invalid. It is that speech-only benchmark performance becomes methodologically ambiguous when interview audio contains clinically explicit symptom language that is recoverable from the waveform.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="g2 stagger mt36">
      <div class="s-card reveal">
        <span class="s-card-num">01</span>
        <h4>Semantic leakage as shortcut learning</h4>
        <p>The paper formalizes semantic leakage as reliance on lexically explicit, depression-related cue spans rather than on distributed acoustic-prosodic evidence alone. This reframes audio-only prediction as an audit problem, not only a model-accuracy problem.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="s-card reveal">
        <span class="s-card-num">02</span>
        <h4>Cue-aware auditing framework</h4>
        <p>The Cue-Aware Agent localizes depression-related cue spans in raw interview audio, maps them to timestamps, and reconstructs preprocessed, cue-only, cue-excluded, and random-control audio views for controlled intervention experiments.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="s-card reveal">
        <span class="s-card-num">03</span>
        <h4>CueFilter front-end</h4>
        <p>CueFilter is a lightweight plug-and-play suppression module. It learns from Agent-derived cue supervision during training, then uses only acoustic features at inference to attenuate cue-dominated regions before downstream prediction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="s-card reveal">
        <span class="s-card-num">04</span>
        <h4>Setting-dependent evidence</h4>
        <p>Across E-DAIC, PDCH, CMDC, and ManDIC, leakage is present but heterogeneous. It becomes especially important in less constrained clinical interactions, where symptom disclosure is longer, more spontaneous, and more closely tied to conversational context.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 3 DATASETS -->
<section id="datasets" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Datasets</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Four clinical interview corpora.</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The audit spans fixed-script distress interviews, semi-structured screening interviews, real clinical consultations, and the newly collected Mandarin Distress Interview Corpus.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="dataset-grid reveal">
      {Object.values(datasetMeta).map((dataset) => (
        <div class="dataset-card" data-dataset={dataset.key}>
          <h4>{dataset.label}</h4>
          <div class="dataset-meta">
            <span class="dataset-badge">{dataset.language}</span>
            <span class="dataset-badge">n={dataset.sample}</span>
            <span class="dataset-badge">{dataset.duration}</span>
          </div>
          <p>{dataset.description}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 4 KEY FINDINGS -->
<section id="findings" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Key Findings</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">What the audit shows.</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The verified cues are not arbitrary transcript fragments. They are clinically meaningful, role-structured, sentiment-distinguishable, and predictive enough to act as shortcuts in speech-only models.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="g2 stagger mt36">
      {keyFindings.map((finding) => (
        <div class="finding-card reveal">
          <div class="finding-num">{finding.id < 10 ? '0' + finding.id : finding.id}</div>
          <h4>{finding.title}</h4>
          <p>{finding.description}</p>
          <div class="finding-metric">{finding.metric} · {finding.dataset}</div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <div class="figure-grid mt36">
      <figure class="figure-card span2 reveal">
        <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-cue-distribution.jpg`} alt="Cue distribution across E-DAIC, PDCH, CMDC, and ManDIC, including frequent cue expressions and relationships with scale scores." />
        <figcaption class="fig-cap">Verified cue distribution across datasets, speaker roles, and depression scale scores. Patient cues show the clearest severity-related tendency in E-DAIC and ManDIC.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="figure-card reveal">
        <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-dsm5.jpg`} alt="Stacked bar chart showing DSM-5 symptom-domain alignment of verified cues across four datasets." />
        <figcaption class="fig-cap">DSM-5 alignment of verified cues: 72.2% in E-DAIC, 83.3% in PDCH, 92.2% in CMDC, and 72.7% in ManDIC match major depressive episode symptom domains.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <div class="metric-tile reveal">
        <div class="metric-value">4 views</div>
        <div class="metric-label">Controlled inputs</div>
        <p>Each recording is reconstructed as preprocessed speech, cue-only audio, cue-excluded audio, and duration-matched random-excluded audio. This separates semantic-cue effects from simple shortening or waveform perturbation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 5 METHODS -->
<section id="methods" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Methods</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Cue localization, intervention, and mitigation.</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The paper separates the heavy offline auditing pipeline from the lightweight deployable mitigation module. The Agent creates reviewed cue supervision; CueFilter uses that supervision to reduce shortcut reliance without transcripts at inference.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pipeline-horizontal-wrap mt36 reveal">
      <div class="pipeline-horizontal">
        {methodSteps.map((step) => (
          <div class="pipe-h-item">
            <div class="pipe-h-head">
              <div class="pipe-num">{step.step}</div>
              <h5>{step.title}</h5>
            </div>
            <p>{step.description}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-grid mt36">
      <figure class="figure-card span2 reveal">
        <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-agent.jpg`} alt="Cue-Aware Agent pipeline covering audio preprocessing, Agent-ASR, speaker assignment, Agent-CUE, verification, and batch reconstruction." />
        <figcaption class="fig-cap">Cue-Aware Agent: audio preprocessing, multi-source ASR, speaker assignment, LLM-assisted cue detection, human verification, and batch reconstruction of controlled audio views.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="figure-card span2 reveal">
        <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-cuefilter.jpg`} alt="CueFilter architecture showing context encoding, depthwise and pointwise convolution, cue scoring, soft gate, renormalization, and downstream backbone models." />
        <figcaption class="fig-cap">CueFilter: a plug-and-play front-end that predicts cue probability from frame-level acoustic features, softly suppresses cue-dominated regions, renormalizes features, and passes the sequence to the unchanged downstream backbone.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 6 RESULTS -->
<section id="results" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Results</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Leakage audit and CueFilter mitigation.</h2>
      <p class="sec-sub">The main evidence is intervention-based: if a speech-only model relies on semantic cues, removing verified patient cue spans should hurt more than removing the same amount of random patient speech.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="metric-strip reveal">
      <div class="metric-tile">
        <div class="metric-value">+1.933</div>
        <div class="metric-label">PDCH DMPF MAE</div>
        <p>DMPF increases from 6.787 to 8.720 after patient cue exclusion, compared with 7.587 under duration-matched random exclusion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-tile">
        <div class="metric-value">+1.365</div>
        <div class="metric-label">CMDC DepAudioNet MAE</div>
        <p>DepAudioNet increases from 2.057 to 3.422 after cue exclusion, while random exclusion decreases to 1.633.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-tile">
        <div class="metric-value">54-67%</div>
        <div class="metric-label">Within-dataset reduction</div>
        <p>CueFilter reduces the cue-minus-random shortcut gap across all four datasets with limited original-input MAE cost.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-tile">
        <div class="metric-value">-60%</div>
        <div class="metric-label">Transfer reduction</div>
        <p>Leave-one-dataset-out evaluation reduces the mean cue-removal gap from 0.261 to 0.104 without target cue annotations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="figure-grid mt36">
      <figure class="figure-card reveal">
        <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-filter-visualization.jpg`} alt="Mel spectrogram comparison of original input, CueFilter, and random-mask conditions." />
        <figcaption class="fig-cap">CueFilter applies localized cue-aware attenuation while preserving surrounding speech structure, unlike a broad random mask.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="figure-card reveal">
        <img src={`${normalizedBaseUrl}figs/semantic-mae.jpg`} alt="Bar charts of original-input MAE for backbone, CueFilter, and reference mask across four datasets." />
        <figcaption class="fig-cap">Original-input MAE cost remains small for CueFilter: +0.009 on E-DAIC, +0.065 on PDCH, +0.015 on CMDC, and +0.032 on ManDIC.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
    <div class="fig-wrap mt36 reveal">
      <table class="results-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Dataset</th>
            <th>Backbone MAE</th>
            <th>CueFilter MAE</th>
            <th>Reference-mask MAE</th>
            <th>CueFilter ΔMAE</th>
            <th>Shortcut-gap reduction</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>E-DAIC</td>
            <td>5.009</td>
            <td>5.018</td>
            <td>5.052</td>
            <td class="delta">+0.009</td>
            <td class="delta">54%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>PDCH</td>
            <td>6.781</td>
            <td>6.846</td>
            <td>6.902</td>
            <td class="delta">+0.065</td>
            <td class="delta">67%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>CMDC</td>
            <td>2.446</td>
            <td>2.461</td>
            <td>2.487</td>
            <td class="delta">+0.015</td>
            <td class="delta">66%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>ManDIC</td>
            <td>7.162</td>
            <td>7.194</td>
            <td>7.232</td>
            <td class="delta">+0.032</td>
            <td class="delta">65%</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="fig-cap">CueFilter functional summary from the current manuscript. The reference mask uses reviewed test cue spans and is included only as an upper-bound comparison, not as a deployable setting.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 7 RESEARCH IMPACT -->
<section id="impact" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Research Impact</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Why this matters.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="g3 stagger mt36">
      <div class="sig-card reveal">
        <div class="sig-cat">Methodological</div>
        <h4>Semantic controls for acoustic claims</h4>
        <p>The framework makes speech-only results more interpretable by reporting cue dependence alongside MAE, RMSE, and R2 instead of treating audio input as automatically semantic-free.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sig-card reveal">
        <div class="sig-cat">Clinical</div>
        <h4>Clearer evidence for biomarkers</h4>
        <p>The findings do not dismiss vocal biomarkers. They show that benchmark performance on interviews should be interpreted only after explicit symptom statements have been localized, removed, or attenuated.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sig-card reveal">
        <div class="sig-cat">Technical</div>
        <h4>Deployable cue suppression</h4>
        <p>CueFilter preserves the downstream model interface and avoids transcripts or LLM calls at inference, making cue-aware mitigation practical for temporal speech backbones.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 8 GLOSSARY -->
<section id="glossary" class="sec">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal">
      <div class="sec-label">Glossary</div>
      <h2 class="sec-title">Key terms explained.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="gloss-grid stagger mt36">
      <div class="gloss-item reveal">
        <div class="gloss-term">Semantic Leakage</div>
        <p>The shortcut-learning phenomenon in which an audio-only model exploits lexically explicit symptom content acoustically embedded in the waveform.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="gloss-item reveal">
        <div class="gloss-term">Cue</div>
        <p>A temporally localized expression of depression-related symptom content, such as low mood, sleep disturbance, guilt, fatigue, anhedonia, or suicidality.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="gloss-item reveal">
        <div class="gloss-term">Cue-Aware Agent</div>
        <p>An offline workflow that combines preprocessing, multi-ASR reconciliation, speaker role attribution, LLM-assisted cue verification, human review, and audio reconstruction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="gloss-item reveal">
        <div class="gloss-term">CueFilter</div>
        <p>A lightweight acoustic front-end that predicts cue probability from frame-level features and softly suppresses cue-dominated regions before downstream depression prediction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="gloss-item reveal">
        <div class="gloss-term">Cue-Excluded Audio</div>
        <p>Participant speech reconstructed after removing verified cue intervals, with random-excluded audio used as a duration-matched control.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

